Radio broadcasting rights are currently held by [[BBC Radio Scotland]], [[BBC Radio nan G<U+00E0>idheal]] and [[BBC Radio 5 Live]].

The Scottish FA sells overseas rights separately from their domestic contract. In Australia, the Scottish Cup is broadcast by [[Setanta Sports Australia]].

== Sponsorship ==
The tournament has been sponsored by a number of institutions in recent years, which have also lent their name to the competition.  These sponsors have included:

* Scottish Health Board (<U+2013>1989)
* [[Wellpark Brewery|Tennents]] Lager (1989<U+2013>2007)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7598521.stm|title=Smith admits Scottish Cup subsidy |date=4 September 2008|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 January 2008}}</ref>
* Subsidised by the [[Scottish FA]] (2007<U+2013>2008)
* [[Homecoming Scotland 2009]] (2008<U+2013>09)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/7659053.stm|title=Homecoming Scottish Cup Unveiled|date=14 October 2008|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 January 2008}}</ref>
* Active Nation (2009<U+2013>10)<ref name="activenation">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/8266911.stm|title=Scottish Cup given new branding|date=21 September 2009|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=21 September 2009}}</ref>
* [[Carling]] (2010-14)<ref name="carling">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/scot_cups/8841891.stm|title=Scottish FA secures four-year Carling sponsorship deal|date=July 21, 2010|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=July 21, 2010}}</ref>

The [[Scottish Government]] in association with businessman [[Willie Haughey]] sponsored the Scottish Cup for the 2008<U+2013>09 and 2009<U+2013>10 seasons, with the 2009 competition being called '''The Homecoming Scottish Cup''' and the 2010 competition called '''The Active Nation Scottish Cup'''.

